	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, this debate has been rehashed a million times, but the warrior-based EQ sites definitely privide information which indicates that damage alone does not determine aggro. The number of &quot;touches&quot; is considered to have a greater impact on aggro that raw damage. <br><br>In other words, a warrior who hits a mob 4 times, for 20 points each hit, is going to greatly outtaunt another warrior who hits the same mob once for 80 points.<br><br>To see this in action, watch a monk and a rogue paired up take down a mob. The monk will typically take aggro, because he uses fast hitting weapons. When the rogue backstabs, the mob will VERY BRIEFLY turn on the rogue, due to the massive damage done by the one hit. However, the monk will quickly regain aggro, despite the fact that their overall damage has not yet caught up to the rogue. Similarly, if I nuke a mob to pull it with my cleric, the melee doesn't have to generate 500+ hp of damage before the mob turns his attention to him instead of me. So Yes, damage does play a role. No taunt is not equal to damage. <br><br>A warrior with a Wurmy MIGHT outdamage a warrior with a lammy, for a very short period of levels, between 20-28 (assuming both are very low strength warriors), but the lammy warrior will typically still outtaunt the wurmy warrior.<br><br>And as far as your example of a warrior with a wurmy holding aggro, the other warrior must not have known how to use the taunt key. I have NEVER had a warrior of similar level to mine take aggro away with a wurmslayer.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
